His married life with Terentia was decorem, but destitute of real sympathy. His early letters from exile are full of tendet expressions, but he seems to have become gradually estranged. He suspects her of fritter- ing away his money under the evil influence of Philo- timus. His last letterss to her reminds us of the, celebrated ‘ chops and tomato sauce‚' which the cnunsel for Mrs. Bardell found so difficolt to construe into the language of affection. Cicero has been blamed for his divorce of Terentia, and his remarriage with the youthful Publilia at the age of 63. But it must be remem- bemd that 63 was not then thought so advanced an

age as it is now. Men began life much later than in modern times, Oicero cannot be said to have begun his political life till he was nearly 40 years of age, and Caesar began his career as a great general at an age at which Alexander was dead and Napoleon had been conquered.
